      "writtenOn": "2020-03-12T05:43:20Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "No Brad.\n\nwhen you say, unlock all resources - that conveys that those set of resources are already locked, and we are trying to unlock all of them - This will be same as calling the releaselock api.\n\nBut not lock all - Means that the client(HMC) can send a lock request and explicitly mention to not lock all the resources under a particular segment.\n\nUse Case:\n\nFor a particular segment(level), we don\u0027t lock anything. But we need to lock the next segment(level).\n\nExample:\n\nEach segment is for one level. For example, the first segment can be CEC (segment size 1, value 1). The second Segment can be a resource under CEC. It can be processor (segment size 1, value 1) or memory (segment size 1, value 2) or partitions (segment size 2, value is the partition id) or a physical IO adapter (segment size 4, value is the adapter\u0027s drc index). The third level can be a resource under the second level. For example, if the second level is a partition, the virtual IO adapters for that partition can the the third level (segment size 2, value is the adpapter id). \n\nIf we want to lock all adapters under a partition, The first segment data is 2 bytes data, for that segment we don\u0027t lock any resource. But in the next segment is the 4 bytes drc index, we can lock one adapter or lock all adapters. Hope this explains the reason for not lock all resources under current resource level.",
      "parentUuid": "74e75610_0f80ac95",
